1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:06,000
Important work often disappears inside chats.

2
00:00:06,000 --> 00:00:12,000
Tracekeep recovers the unfinished loops behind everyday ideas, decisions, and follow-ups.

3
00:00:12,000 --> 00:00:24,000
Tracekeep starts where the thought happens: in the conversation. Say what to remember, then ask what unfinished work is worth resuming.

4
00:00:24,000 --> 00:00:36,000
This screen uses synthetic data and does not claim automatic access to every chat.

5
00:00:36,000 --> 00:00:46,000
The capture is now a real local Tracekeep record with its Codex source attached.

6
00:00:46,000 --> 00:00:56,000
It waits in Review before acceptance. The Dashboard is the control room, not the required daily entry point.

7
00:00:56,000 --> 00:01:07,000
The same follow-up can appear in more than one place. Tracekeep marks a possible duplicate and merges only when asked.

8
00:01:07,000 --> 00:01:18,000
Both pieces of evidence remain inspectable. Undo removes the added link without deleting the original work.

9
00:01:18,000 --> 00:01:29,000
Today highlights at most three priorities. An item can move to Waiting, Next week, Done, or back to Today.

10
00:01:29,000 --> 00:01:40,000
The latest change can be undone immediately.

11
00:01:40,000 --> 00:01:50,000
Local SQLite FTS5 search returns the record together with its human-readable source.

12
00:01:50,000 --> 00:02:00,000
Tracekeep helps the user return to evidence instead of trusting an unsupported memory.

13
00:02:00,000 --> 00:02:09,000
Restricted content stays out of ordinary search and sanitized export.

14
00:02:09,000 --> 00:02:18,000
The competition build keeps a zero-dollar external budget, with paid providers and platform APIs disabled.

15
00:02:18,000 --> 00:02:28,000
Codex and GPT-5.6 turned product decisions into implementation, tests, privacy checks, and a judge-ready Windows release.

16
00:02:28,000 --> 00:02:36,300
Tracekeep remembers where you stopped, what comes next, and why it was worth continuing.
